Problem 1: (7 points) ISLR Chapter 2 Problem 9. This problem is an exploratory analysis of the Auto dataset. The dataset is available on Webcourses in the file Auto.csv Auto.csv. This dataset is referenced in the text of both Chapters 2 and 3 and you can look at the information there as a guideline. One important thing to note is that you should omit rows with missing entries using the na.omit() function in R or the or the df.dropna() function in pandas, where df is your dataframe. (Note: In general, omitting NA values might bias your results. But data imputation can be involved so for now we will just remove missing entries).

  1. This exercise involves the Auto data set studied in the lab. Make sure that the missing values have been removed from the data.

import pandas as pd;
file_path = 'C:/Users/danma/Downloads/STA 4364/Assigment 1/Auto.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
#omiting NA values
df.dropna()
#could not set horsepower to integer because of non integer values identified in column '?'
df = df[df['horsepower'] != '?']
#reassigning horsepower column as an integer column
df['horsepower'] = df['horsepower'].astype(int)
#prints dataframe head

(f) Suppose that we wish to predict gas mileage (mpg) on the basis of the other variables. Do your plots suggest that any of the other variables might be useful in predicting mpg? Justify your answer.

The plots suggest that several variables would assist in predicting gas mileage(mpg), variables include displacement, horsepower, weight, and cylinders. These are seen across the first 5 plots at the top. Higher cylinders resulting in lower mpg, higher displacement resulting in lower mpg, higher horsepower resulting in lower mpg, and higher weight resulting in lower mpg.

Problem 2¶

Problem 2: (6 points) This problem will involve making plots to summarize information from the dataset CodParasite.txt CodParasite.txt. This datasets contain information about parasite infections for cod fish in addition to different attributes of each fish that might be related to parasite prevelance. To read a .txt file in R, use read.table(file name.txt, header=TRUE).

In [6]:
import pandas as pd;
#importing data
file_path = 'C:/Users/danma/Downloads/STA 4364/Assigment 1/CodParasite.txt'
df = pd.read_table(file_path)
df.dropna()

import numpy as np
#Log transform of Intensity adding 1 to each entry
df['Intensity'] = df['Intensity'].apply(np.log1p)

Make a boxplot of the number of parasites (Intensity) conditional on area, sex, stage, and year. You should make 4 plots total, and the number of boxplots in each plot should equal the number of categories in the conditional variable.

In [7]:
#plotting
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

#creating 4 plots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=2,figsize=(20, 20),dpi=500)
sns.boxplot(y=df['Intensity'],x=df['Area'], ax=axs[0,0],palette="Set2",medianprops={"color": "red"})
sns.boxplot(y=df['Intensity'],x=df['Sex'], ax=axs[0,1],palette="Set2",medianprops={"color": "red"})
sns.boxplot(y=df['Intensity'],x=df['Stage'], ax=axs[1,0],palette="Set2",medianprops={"color": "red"})
sns.boxplot(y=df['Intensity'],x=df['Year'], ax=axs[1,1],palette="Set2",medianprops={"color": "red"})
Out[7]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Year', ylabel='Intensity'>

Comment on which conditional variables appear to have an association with the number of parasites. Update: You might get more easily interpretable results if you take a log transform of Intensity (before taking the log, add 1 to each entry to prevent errors from taking the log of 0 entries) before making the boxplots. Either way is OK for your submission.

Area appears to have association with the number of parasites due to one median not overlapping, varying whisker lengths, and significant outliers.

Sex appears to have no association with the number of parasites due to strong overlap with medians and whisker lengths.

Stage appears to have some association with the number of parasites due to stage 3 being significantly smaller than the other batches of data and number of outliers, but overall, there appears to be no association due to similar whisker lengths and overlapping medians.

Year appears to have some association with the number of parasites due to one median, 2000, barely reaching out of bounds of another batch of data, 2001. Other factors include varying whisker lengths, and a significant number of outliers.
